          "body": "Verses 5-9 shift from decree to divine lament. The triple rhetorical question of verse 5 — 'Who will have pity... who will mourn... who will turn aside to ask?' — is not seeking an answer. It is announcing that no one will. Jerusalem has so thoroughly forfeited covenant loyalty that even the normal human responses of pity and mourning have been withdrawn. Verse 6 then delivers the chapter's most startling line: 'I am tired of relenting.' The Hebrew word *nacham* is the word used of God's grief that moved Him to change course — the very word that described His response to Moses' intercession (Exodus 32:14) and to Samuel's era (1 Samuel 15:29, where Nathan says God is 'not a man that He should relent' precisely because He had already decided). God has relented so many times, extended patience so repeatedly, that the capacity for further relenting is — within the covenantal framework of this moment — exhausted. The imagery of judgment in verses 7-9 is harrowing: winnowing at the gates, bereaved children, widows outnumbering the sand of the sea, a destroyer at noonday. The mother who bore seven sons — the pinnacle of covenant blessing (cf. 1 Samuel 2:5) — watches her sun set in midday. The inversion of blessing is total."
