          "title": "The prophet's complaint — woe to me, my mother (15:10-18)",
          "body": "The chapter pivots abruptly at verse 10 from divine oracle to prophetic lament. Jeremiah's 'Woe to me' is the cry of a man who has been faithful and received only persecution in return. He was born to be 'a man of strife and a man of contention to all the land' — not because he chose conflict but because the word God gave him created it. He has done nothing wrong economically (neither lent nor borrowed), and yet the whole land curses him. This is the prophet's existential crisis at its sharpest: the calling is real, the cost is unbearable, and the equation does not balance. God's brief answer in verses 11-14 is more oracular than comforting — the enemy will one day plead with Jeremiah (v. 11), but for now the 'iron from the north' (Babylon) is unstoppable (v. 12) and Judah's treasures will be plundered (vv. 13-14). The lament resumes in verse 15 at a deeper register: Jeremiah asks God to remember him, take notice of him, and avenge him on his persecutors. Verse 16 then offers the chapter's most intimate confession: 'Your words were found and I ate them, and Your words became for me a joy and the delight of my heart.' The image of eating the divine word (cf. Ezekiel 3:1-3; Revelation 10:9-10) describes total internalization — the word is not merely studied but absorbed. Yet that very absorption has cost him everything: he sat alone, excluded from community, filled with God's indignation (v. 17). The complaint peaks in verse 18 with an accusation so bold it verges on blasphemy: 'Will You indeed be to me like a deceptive stream, with water that is unreliable?' The *akhzav* — the wadi that promises water and runs dry — is Jeremiah's darkest metaphor for God. It is the language of a man whose theology of divine faithfulness is being crushed by his experience of divine silence."
