        "excerpt": "Woe to me, my mother, that you have borne me as a man of strife and a man of contention to all the land! … Why has my pain been perpetual and my wound incurable, refusing to be healed? Will You indeed be to me like a deceptive stream with water that is unreliable?",
        "body": "Jeremiah's confessions are among the most theologically significant texts in the Old Testament precisely because they are included unedited. The lament of vv. 10-18 is not a low point the canon is embarrassed about — it is Scripture. The Psalmic lament tradition (Psalms 22, 88, 102) establishes the legitimacy of raw complaint directed at God; what makes Jeremiah's confessions distinctive is that they come from a prophet in the middle of active ministry, not merely a sufferer in private anguish. The prophet who delivers God's words publicly must wrestle with those same words privately.\n\nVerse 16 is the passage's most intimate verse and one of the most important in the book: 'Your words were found and I ate them, and Your words became for me a joy and the delight of my heart.' The eating metaphor for Scripture internalization (cf. Ezekiel 3:1-3; Revelation 10:9-10; Psalm 19:10; 119:103) describes not study but absorption — the word becomes constitutive of the prophet's inner world. And yet that very absorption — being called by God's name, belonging to the LORD God of Hosts — has cost Jeremiah the normal pleasures of community. He 'did not sit in the circle of merrymakers' (v. 17) not from ascetic choice but because God's hand upon him made the merrymakers' world inaccessible. The joy of v. 16 and the isolation of v. 17 are not contradictions; they are the two sides of genuine prophetic calling.\n\nThe complaint peaks at verse 18 with the *akhzav* image — God compared to a deceptive stream. In the ancient Near East, wadis (seasonal riverbeds) were treacherous: travelers who camped near them for water could wake to find them dry. The image in Job 6:15-20 uses the same metaphor for friends who disappoint. Jeremiah turns it on God Himself. This is the confession's most dangerous moment — and the point at which God will intervene. The lament is not condemned as faithless (God answers, not abandons), but it has crossed from honest complaint into something that requires correction. Peter Craigie (*Word Biblical Commentary on Jeremiah*, 1991) notes that the confessions model the full range of what honest prayer in relationship with God looks like — including the accusation that the relationship has been violated.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Akhzav* (deceptive stream, v. 18) is also used in Micah 1:14 for cities that fail to deliver on their promise. *Netsach* (perpetual, v. 18) means 'unto victory/endlessness' — it is the same word used of God's eternal faithfulness in Lamentations 3:18; Jeremiah uses it here of his own unending suffering, turning the vocabulary of divine eternity against his own pain."
